  "body": "news yobo community Help Donate Press Submit News Contact About Arts Community Arts Film, Music & Theatre Painting Reading and Writing Visual Business Community Investment Corporate Social Responsibility Finance Social Entrepreneurshp Sustainability Trade and Barter Education Access/ Resources Alternative Child Development Literacy Environment Conservation Recycling Sustainability Food & Health Accessibility/ Treatment Agriculture Mind and Body Trade Inspiring Humanitarian Aid Philanthropy and Charity Social Action Peace Conflict Resolution Cooperation Human Rights Kindness Non-Violence PR Science & Technology Green Innovation Vital Resources The Lighter Side Humor In Brief Photo/ Illustration Poetry Recipes Video News Denmark Invests the Most in Clean Energy per GDP Yale Environment 360 May 10th, 2011 Tweet Credit: Denmark Wind Farm/WikiMedia China leads the world in total investments in renewable energy and energy efficiency, although as a percentage of overall economic activity Denmark ranks first in clean-tech spending, according to a report by the conservation group WWF. The report says that China is currently investing $65 billion a year in clean tech, with renewable energy spending growing at 77 percent a year since 2008. The U.S. spends $45 billion a year on clean technologies, with those investments growing by 28 percent a year since 2008. But Denmark, which spends $9.4 billion a year on renewable energy and energy efficiency, is the world leader when clean-tech investment is taken as a percentage of gross domestic product; Denmark’s clean-tech investments equal 3.1 percent of GDP. Using that measure, China ranks second, spending 1.4 percent of GDP on clean tech. The U.S. ranks 17th, with clean-tech investments accounting for 0.3 percent of GDP, according to the report, which gathered data on 38 countries. Measuring clean-tech spending as a percentage of GDP, the remaining countries in the top five are Germany, Brazil, and Denmark. Story originally appeared at Yale Environment 360 Share and Enjoy: These icons link to social bookmarking sites where readers can share and discover new web pages. ( +4 rating) Loading ... You might also enjoy: Economics for a Blue Planet Scientists Investigate Water Memory Getting Better at Going Green Denmark’s New Prime Minister Launches Global Green Growth Forum With 200 World Leaders And UN Secretary General Arup Proposes ‘Cluster’ City for Water Starved Area of China Leave a Comment Click here to cancel reply. What's Hot Popular Posts EcoAlert: Harvesting the … Why Does Walking Barefoot… Decade of the African Wom… 7 Summer Reads to Live Gr… Same-Sex Marriage Brings … Recent Comments Adults With Disabilities Learn To Perform At College Of Their Own « About Handicapped Aids on Bilal’s Got Some New Tricks! Adults With Disabilities Learn To Perform At College Of Their Own « About Handicapped Aids on Adults With Disabilities Learn To Perform At College Of Their Own Archives Select Month May 2012 (20) April 2012 (39) March 2012 (39) February 2012 (41) January 2012 (40) December 2011 (41) November 2011 (45) October 2011 (42) September 2011 (50) August 2011 (54) July 2011 (45) June 2011 (57) May 2011 (69) April 2011 (71) March 2011 (81) February 2011 (72) January 2011 (86) December 2010 (72) November 2010 (91) October 2010 (96) September 2010 (111) August 2010 (119) July 2010 (146) June 2010 (163) May 2010 (119) April 2010 (143) March 2010 (159) February 2010 (147) January 2010 (100) December 2009 (80) November 2009 (15) October 2009 (3) September 2009 (2) July 2009 (1) March 2009 (1) Dig Deeper Environment ‘Leftover Love’: Take Your Own Containers Exploring the Role of Continuous Improvement in Sustainability Birthing Justice: Our Hope Is In Our Struggle – Reclaiming Life And Land In Honduras Food & Health ‘Leftover Love’: Take Your Own Containers Birthing Justice: Our Hope Is In Our Struggle – Reclaiming Life And Land In Honduras Nine Steps To Achieving Flow In Your Work Inspirat